About the project

I first saw this course listed in the transferable skills course list for my doctoral program. The course looked interesting and useful, so I decided to register.

As I have no previous experience in R, RStudio or GitHub, I’m looking forward to first learning to use these tools properly. Then, I expect to use the tools to do data analysis and visualization, as well as to learn more about open data and open science.

My GitHub repository is at: https://github.com/sr-hel/IODS-project

Regression and model validation

The dataset

We begin by reading in the learning2014 dataset and exploring it:

learning2014 <- read.csv("data/learning2014.csv")
dim(learning2014)

##  $ surf    : num  2.58 3.17 2.25 2.25 2.83 ...

We see that the dataset consists of 166 observations of 7 variables. The variables are gender, age, attitude, exam points, and three combined variables deep, stra and surf, which combine answers regarding deep, strategic and surface learning, respectively.

Let us plot the distributions of the variables to look at their relationships:

library(GGally)
## Loading required package: ggplot2

p

Looking at the distributions of the variables first, we note that there are about twice as many women compared to men in the dataset and the ages are mostly concentrated around the early 20s. Men appear to have higher attitude scores than women on average. Deep learning scores are distributed quite high in general, while strategic and surface learning scores are more evenly distributed across the full range. Women appear to have higher strategic and surface learning scores than men on average. The exam point distribution leans towards the top end of the range.

We see that the strongest correlations are between exam points and attitude, and between surface and deep learning. A higher attitude score tends to correlate with higher exam points, and a higher deep learning score tends to correlate with a lower surface learning score.

Linear regression

We will now consider a linear regression model where exam points is the target variable. We choose attitude, strategic learning and surface learning as our three explanatory variables, given that they are the variables most strongly correlated with exam points:

model <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = learning2014)
summary(model)

We see that the p-value listed in the Pr(>|t|) column for the attitude variable is extremely small, thus attitude can be said to have a statistically significant relationship with the target variable, exam points. The strategic learning and surface learning variables however do not, thus we will remove the least significant one (the latter) and fit the model again:

model <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra, data = learning2014)

The statistical significance of the intercept and the attitude variable have increased, but the strategic learning variable is still not statistically significant enough. Therefore we remove it from the model, and we’re left with a model with just the attitude variable:

model <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
summary(model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.6372     1.8303   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## attitude      3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

In this final model, the statistical significance of the attitude variable has increased even further, and the estimate for the attitude fit parameter is 3.5255. This means that when the attitude score goes up by 1, the expected exam points go up by about 3.5255.

A Multiple R-squared value of 0.1906 means that about 19% of the variation in exam points is explained by the variation in attitude.

Model validation

Finally, we consider the following diagnostic plots:

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model, which = c(1, 2, 5))

Our model has a number of built-in assumptions. First, since it is a linear regression model, we assume that the exam points variable has a linear relationship with the attitude variable. Second, we assume that the errors of the model are 1) normally distributed, 2) not correlated, and 3) have constant variance.

The QQ-plot tells us how well our fit matches the assumption of normally distributed errors. From the plot we see that our fit follows the dotted line quite closely, therefore agreeing with the normality of errors assumption.

The Residuals vs Fitted plot tells us how well our fit matches the assumption of constant variance of errors. Given that the plot does not show any particular patterns, our fit agrees with this assumption as well.

Finally, the Residuals vs Leverage plot tells us whether a single observation has an unusually large impact on our model. Since no points stand out in the plot, and the maximum values of leverage are fairly small (< 0.05), our fit has no such issues.

The dataset

We begin by reading in the alc data set:

alc <- read.csv("data/alc.csv")
colnames(alc)
##  [1] "school"     "sex"        "age"        "address"    "famsize"

This is a joined data set, combining student data from two Portuguese schools. The data set describes school performance in mathematics and Portuguese language, but it also contains information regarding student background, activities and social factors. Of particular interest to us are the alc_use and high_use variables, which describe student alcohol consumption.

In this analysis, we study the relationships between alcohol consumption and the following four variables: G3, famrel, internet and studytime. G3 is the final year school grade, famrel describes family relationships, internet stands for internet access at home, and studytime is the student’s weekly study time.

Before looking at the data, we would expect high alcohol consumption to correlate with lower final year grades, worse family relationships, no internet access at home, and less weekly study time.

We will now load in the necessary libraries and then we’ll go through the relationships between the variables one by one.

Logistic regression model

m <- glm(high_use ~ G3 + famrel + internet + studytime, data = alc, family = "binomial")
summary(m)

## studytime    0.5709640 0.4176457  0.7670617

Above, we have listed a summary of our logistic regression model, the coefficients of the model as odd ratios and their confidence intervals.

From the p-values of the summary we can see that out of all the variables we considered, study time has by far the most significant statistical relationship with alcohol consumption. Family relationships also have some statistical significance, final year grades have very little, and internet access has none. The estimated coefficients are negative for the three variables of significance, which tells us that when study scores, family relations or study time goes down, the prediction for high alcohol consumption goes up.

We can see this also in the odd ratios. We note that the odd ratios for the variables studytime, famrel and G3 are less than zero. This means that they are negatively associated with alcohol consumption, i.e. the odds of high alcohol consumption become lower when the explanatory variable goes through a positive unit change.

The logistic regression model agrees with our hypothesis for the variables studytime, famrel and G3, but disagrees with our hypothesis for the variable internet, which turned out to be statistically insignificant.

Predictions

We drop the internet variable, and look at the predictive performance of our model with the remaining three explanatory variables.

m <- glm(high_use ~ studytime + famrel + G3, data = alc, family = "binomial")
probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)
g <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = probability, y = high_use, col = prediction))
g + geom_point()

table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   255   13
##    TRUE    107    7

We see that our model does a decent job of predicting when there is no high alcohol consumption (with only 13 false positives), but it has issues recognizing when there is (it missed 107 cases). We can also consider the training error:

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.3141361
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = 0)
## [1] 0.2984293
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = 1)
## [1] 0.7015707

Above, we have computed the total proportion of inaccurately classified observations for our model, as well as the corresponding proportions for two simple guesses: always assuming that there is no high alcohol consumption, and always assuming that there is. In this case, the simple guessing strategy that there is no high alcohol consumption has slightly less error (0.2984) than our model (0.3141). The other guessing strategy of always assuming high alcohol consumption yields much worse results at 0.7015.

Bonus: Cross-validation

library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m, K = 10)
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.3246073

We perform 10-fold cross-validation of our model, and find a mean prediction error of > 0.30. The performance of this model is therefore clearly worse than the model considered in the DataCamp tutorial with error 0.26.

As seen from the above summary, we have scaled all the variables such that their means are zero. We now create a categorical variable of the crime rate by using the quantiles as the break points. We also divide the data set into train and test sets, so that 80% of all data belongs to the train set:

boston_scaled <- as.data.frame(boston_scaled)

bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, label = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)

n <- nrow(boston_scaled)

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

From the relative length of the arrows in the plot it is apparent that the variable rad has by far the largest impact on the class grouping. From the “proportion of trace” listing we also see that the LD1 discriminant (represented by the x-axis in the plot) explains about 95% of the variance between the groups.

We can now use our linear discriminant analysis fit to predict the crime classes on the test data. Since we know the correct classes, we can compare the results to see how accurate our prediction is:

correct_classes <- test$crime
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       15      12        3    0
##   med_low   10      15        5    0
##   med_high   0       7       14    1
##   high       0       0        0   20

The predictions of our LDA model appear to be very good for the “high” class and passable for the “med_low” and “low” classes on average. For the “med_high” class, our model sometimes seems to have trouble separating between “med_high” and “med_low”. In conclusion, our model can accurately predict whether the crime rate of the suburb is in the “high” category.

K-means clustering

Finally, let us consider K-means clustering. We reload the data set and scale it again. We calculate the Euclidean distances between observations and run the K-means algorithm with the number of clusters fixed to three, initially:

data('Boston')
boston_scaled <- scale(Boston)

dist_eu <- dist(boston_scaled)
km <- kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 3)
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)

For three clusters, there does not appear to be any variables that would cleanly separate the different clusters from each other.

Let us try to figure out the optimal number of clusters by looking at the within cluster sum of squares (WCSS). We calculate the values of total WCSS for 1-10 clusters and plot the results:

library(ggplot2)
set.seed(123)
k_max <- 10
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled, k)$tot.withinss})
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

Since the value of total WCSS drops radically for two clusters, this seems like the optimal value. We run the K-means algorithm again for two clusters:

km <- kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 2)
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)

In this plot, the two clusters appear to be most clearly separated for the variables rad and tax, thus these must be the strongest separators for the clusters. This means that the suburbs of Boston can be nicely grouped based on accessibility to radial highways and full-value property-tax rate.

Principal component analysis

Non-standardized data

We first perform principal component analysis on the non-standardized human data:

Since we have not scaled (standardized) our data, the variable with the largest standard deviation dominates. The standard deviation is represented by the length of the arrow, and in this case we see that it is GNI that dominates over all the other variables. It follows that our first principle component PC1 is strongly correlated with GNI, and in fact 100% of the variation in the data is explained by the first principle component. This means that the analysis has essentially reduced the dimension of the data set to one. This is not necessarily accurate, so let us repeat the analysis by first standardizing the data:

Standardized data

human_std <- scale(human)
pca_human <- prcomp(human_std)
s <- summary(pca_human)
s
## Importance of components:
##                           PC1    PC2     PC3     PC4     PC5     PC6     PC7
## Standard deviation     2.0708 1.1397 0.87505 0.77886 0.66196 0.53631 0.45900
## Proportion of Variance 0.5361 0.1624 0.09571 0.07583 0.05477 0.03595 0.02634
## Cumulative Proportion  0.5361 0.6984 0.79413 0.86996 0.92473 0.96069 0.98702
##                            PC8
## Standard deviation     0.32224
## Proportion of Variance 0.01298
## Cumulative Proportion  1.00000
pca_pr <- round(100*s$importance[2, ], digits = 1)
pc_lab <- paste0(names(pca_pr), " (", pca_pr, "%)")
biplot(pca_human, cex = c(0.8, 1), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"), xlab = pc_lab[1], ylab = pc_lab[2])

We see that now the variables mort, birth, eduexp, lifeexp, GNI and edu2r are correlated with the first principal component PC1, which captures about 54% of the variability of the data. Orthogonal to this component is the second principal component PC2, correlated with the labr and parli variables and explaining about 16% of the variability. Together they explain about 70% of the variability of the data set. Here we have a two-dimensional reduction of our data set where all the original variables have a comparable contribution (standard deviation).

To recap, the difference between the two results is due to the fact that principal component analysis assumes the features with larger variance to be more important than the features with smaller variance. In the non-standardized case, GNI dominates over all the other variables as the only important one. In the (scaled) standardized case, the other variables are properly represented as well.

Our interpretation is that these country-based human development indices can be effectively reduced to two dimensions: the first principal component dimension PC1 describes health, knowledge and standard of living. The second principal component dimension PC2 describes the proportion of females in the labour force and in decision-making positions. According to the principal component analysis, these two aspects (PC1 and PC2) are orthogonal, i.e. not correlated.

Analysis of longitudinal data

The RATS dataset

We begin by reading in the RATS data set:

RATSL <- read.csv("data/RATSL.csv", row.names = 1)
RATSL$ID <- factor(RATSL$ID)
RATSL$Group <- factor(RATSL$Group)

dim(RATSL)

The RATS data set consists of 176 observations of 5 variables (of longitudinal data). The data is from a study on the weight gain of three groups of rats (16 rats total) on different diets over a period of 64 days.

We plot the weight developments of the rat groups as follows:

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(RATSL, aes(x = Time, y = Weight, group = ID)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(. ~ Group, labeller = label_both) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(RATSL$Weight), max(RATSL$Weight)))

From the plots we see that the rats in Group 1 are about half the weight of the rats in the other groups, and there are twice as many of them. In Group 2, we see that there is an outlier rat of a much heavier weight than the others. Overall, it appears that all rats gained weight during the study, but rats in Groups 2 and 3 gained more absolute weight than the rats in Group 1.

To compare the weight gain better, let us standardize the weights:

RATSL <- RATSL %>%
  group_by(Time) %>%
  mutate(stdWeight = (Weight - mean(Weight))/sd(Weight)) %>%
  ungroup()

ggplot(RATSL, aes(x = Time, y = stdWeight, group = ID)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(. ~ Group, labeller = label_both) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "standardized Weight")

The standardized weight plots tell us that the rats in Group 2 appeared to gain relatively more weight on average than rats in the other groups. Compared to their initial weights, rats in Group 3 appear to have gained the least weight, with the rats in Group 2 positioned somewhere in between.

Next, we will look at the mean response profile.

n <- RATSL$Time %>% unique() %>% length()

RATSS <- RATSL %>%
  group_by(Group, Time) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(Weight), se = sd(Weight)/sqrt(n)) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'Group' (override with `.groups` argument)
ggplot(RATSS, aes(x = Time, y = mean, linetype = Group, shape = Group)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = c(1,2,3)) +
  geom_point(size=3) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(1,2,3)) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean - se, ymax = mean + se, linetype="1"), width=0.3) +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.9,0.5)) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(Weight) +/- se(Weight)")

From the mean response profile plot we can tell that the groups are clearly different from one another, because the standard errors do not overlap. We can also see what we already noted on earlier: the mean weights of each group increase during the study, and the rats in Group 2 appear to be gaining weight faster than the rats in Group 3, since the corresponding lines in the plot are getting closer to each other with time.

Let us then consider the mean summary measure.

RATSL8S <- RATSL %>%
  filter(Time > 1) %>%
  group_by(Group, ID) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(Weight)) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'Group' (override with `.groups` argument)
ggplot(RATSL8S, aes(x = Group, y = mean)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun.y = "mean", geom = "point", shape=23, size=4, fill = "white") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(Weight), weeks 2-9")
## Warning: `fun.y` is deprecated. Use `fun` instead.

There appears to be more variability in Group 2, which is understandable due to the heavy outlier we noted on earlier, seen here as a black dot at a weight of almost 600 grams. We also see some less drastic outliers in the other groups. Since these outliers may bias our analysis, we’ll filter them out:

RATSL8S1 <- RATSL8S %>%
  filter(mean > 250 & mean < 550 & (mean < 475 | mean > 525))

ggplot(RATSL8S1, aes(x = Group, y = mean)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun.y = "mean", geom = "point", shape=23, size=4, fill = "white") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(Weight), weeks 2-9")
## Warning: `fun.y` is deprecated. Use `fun` instead.

We have no more outliers. We can see some more variability with Groups 1 and 2 when compared to Group 3, but we’d like to perform a formal test to be sure. Let us do exactly that. We’ll consider the observations of day 1 as a baseline in what follows.

RATS <- read.table("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/KimmoVehkalahti/MABS/master/Examples/data/rats.txt", sep="", header=TRUE)

RATSL8S2 <- RATSL8S %>%
  mutate(baseline = RATS$WD1)

fit <- lm(mean ~ baseline + Group, data = RATSL8S2)
summary(fit)

But we can also see that the Group variable has a p-value of 0.07586, which implies that the choice of group actually has no real statistical significance on the mean.

The BPRS dataset

Let us consider the BPRS data set next. We read in the data:

BPRSL <- read.csv("data/BPRSL.csv", row.names = 1)
BPRSL$subject <- BPRSL$subject + 20*(BPRSL$treatment == 2)
BPRSL$treatment <- factor(BPRSL$treatment)
BPRSL$subject <- factor(BPRSL$subject)

dim(BPRSL)

The BPRS data set consists of 176 observations of 6 variables (of longitudinal data). The data records the brief psychiatric rating scale (bprs) measured from 40 male subjects divided into two treatment groups, over a period of 8 weeks.

We plot the psychiatric rating over the treatment period as follows:

ggplot(BPRSL, aes(x = week, y = bprs, group = subject)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(. ~ treatment, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(BPRSL$bprs), max(BPRSL$bprs)))

It looks like in the case of treatment 1, the bprs rating goes down during the treatment for most subjects. Things are a little less clear for the treatment 2 group, and we see that we again have an outlier in the second group.

We will ignore the longitudinal nature of the data for now. We fit a multiple linear regression model, where bprs is the target variable and week + treatment are the explanatory variables. We find the following model:
